Rating: 3
This is a very good sauce. For the purists you may like to try the following. I was in Bologna in 1969 and this was the recipe for bolognese from one of the oldest, family owned restaurants. Use flank or skirt from the belly of the cow for flavour. Mince it yourself. It should look minced but not too fine. Two cooks knives & a wooden chopping board works well. For EVERY 300g of meat use the following. 50g of finely chopped pancetta. 30g [by weight] of good quality olive oil, 30g ea. of very f. chopped onion, carrot & celery. 1 cup of white wine. Lots of freshly ground nutmeg [ essential & not discernable in the finished sauce], freshly gr. black pepper & a little salt. 2 tbls of good tomato paste and one cup of water [fresh or tinned tomatoes can be too acidic for this sauce]. Follow the same cooking methods. This sauce relies on the finest ingredients and very, very long and careful cooking. Tagliatelle is traditional but any FRESH pasta is essential for this rich and very thick meat sauce.

