OK. I tried this recipe recently after being disappointed by the Bon Appetite Bolognese recipe (Sept. 2002). Carefully read the reviews and the ratings for Mario Batali's version and was discouraged from trying it for two reasons. It included garlic and it did not include nutmeg. After trying this recipe, I think I made the right decision. I used this recipe as a starting point and added a few ingredients and used techniques that I culled from other recipes (Lidia Bastianich, for one) and reviews. I used ground beef pork and veal. I also used about a half pound of chicken livers. I sauteed these in a separate pan while I was sauteeing the veggies. I also included some leftover diced slab prociutto in the veggie saute. Poured of the fat (lots of it) and added the browned choppped meat to the sauteed vegatbles.Tripled the reduction times on the milk and wine , partly because I doubled the recipe. When I added the tomatoes, I also added some fresh thyme, a cup of leftover canned beef stock , 2 Tbs. of concentrated tomato paste and 3 bay leaves. I also increased the simmering time to nearly four hours. The result? Fantastic! Thick , rich, beautiful color and complex flavor.Didn't miss the garlic at all and the chicken livers were totally undetectable. (I know this because my kids ate it.) I will definitely keep this one as my standard recipe for Bolognese sauce. P.S. Thanks Marina from Cincinatti for your post. I relied heavily on your input for my attempt at this classic comfort food.

